  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "9CGFSn4OHO+bar4bZhO5Swsei0g=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nSwarm's unit of storage is a **4KB content-addressed chunk (CAC)**. All data, regardless of size, is split into these chunks and reassembled via a Merkle hash tree.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Max payload per chunk: 4096 bytes\n- Chunk address = `Keccak256(span || BMT_root(payload))` where span is an 8-byte total-length prefix\n- Self-verifying: any peer can recompute the address from the bytes\n- Files larger than 4KB form a **hash tree**: leaf chunks hold data, intermediate chunks hold 128 child references (32 bytes each)\n- The root chunk's address is the file's reference (32 bytes)\n- Encrypted files drop branching factor to 64 because each ref becomes 64 bytes (32-byte address + 32-byte decryption key)\n\n## Why it matters\n\nThe adapter uploads encrypted JSON via `POST /bytes`; the Bee node handles chunking automatically. We never touch raw chunks directly, but understanding this layer explains why reference sizes differ between plain and encrypted uploads.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
